{{sociology}}
A '''sexual network''' is a [[social network]] that is defined by the sexual relationships within a set of individuals.

==Studies and discoveries==
Like other forms of social networks, sexual networks can be formally studied using the mathematics of [[graph theory]] and [[network theory]].<ref name="Liljeros2003">{{cite journal |last= Liljeros |first= Fredrik |author2=Christofer R. Edling |author3=Luis A. Nunes Amaral |year= 2003|title= Sexual networks: implications for the transmission of sexually transmitted infections |journal= Microbes and Infection|volume= 5 |pages= 189–196 |publisher= Science direct |doi=10.1016/s1286-4579(02)00058-8}}</ref><ref name="Liljeros2001">{{cite journal |last= Liljeros |first= Fredrik |author2=Christofer R. Edling |author3=Luis A. Nunes Amaral |author4=H. Eugene Stanley |author5=Yvonne Aberg |year= 2001|title= The web of human sexual contacts |journal= Nature|volume= 411 |pages= 907–908 |doi=10.1038/35082140 |pmid=11418846|arxiv=cond-mat/0106507 }}</ref>

Recent [[epidemiology|epidemiological]] studies<ref name="Rocha2010">{{cite journal |last= Rocha |first= L.E.C. |author2=Fredrik Liljeros |author3=Petter Holme |year= 2010|title= Information dynamics shape the sexual networks of Internet-mediated prostitution |journal= Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume= 107 | issue=13 |pages= 5706–5713 |doi=10.1073/pnas.0914080107 |pmid=20231480 |pmc=2851932|bibcode=2010PNAS..107.5706R }}</ref>  have investigated sexual networks, and suggest that the statistical properties of sexual networks are crucial to the spread of [[sexually transmitted disease]]s (STDs). Sub-graphs, both large and small, can be defined within the overall sexual network graph; for example, people who frequent particular bars or clubs, belong to a particular ethnic group or take part in a particular type of sexual activity, or are part of a particular outbreak of an STD.  In particular, [[assortative mixing]] between people with large numbers of sexual partners seems to be an important factor in the spread of STD.

In a surprising result, mathematical models predict that the sexual network graph for the human race appears to have a single [[giant component]] that indirectly links almost all people who have had more than one sexual partner, and a great many of those who have had only one sexual partner (if their one sexual partner was themselves part of the giant component). {{Citation needed|date=August 2013}}.

For more detailed epidemiological work, the time sequence of sexual contacts is important.

